TCGAbiolinks lecture

In this lecture we will go over how to install and use the package TCGAbiolinks for querying, downloading, and analyzing publicly available TCGA cancer data.

Installation

You must have the latest version of R, Bioconductor BiocManager, and TCGAbiolinks installed for the package to work correctly. Check your R version by running the command version in the console. If it is earlier than 3.6.1, please re-install R. Select a mirror, then choose the correct installer for your system.

Install BiocManager and TCGAbiolinks:

if (!requireNamespace("BiocManager", quietly = TRUE))
    install.packages("BiocManager")

BiocManager::install("TCGAbiolinks")

While on campus, you need to set proxies in order to talk to the database

Sys.setenv(http_proxy="proxy.swmed.edu:3128")
Sys.setenv(https_proxy="proxy.swmed.edu:3128")

Load the pacakge and set your working directory

library(TCGAbiolinks)

setwd("~/r_nanocourse_2020/")

TCGAbiolinks

Queries

Queries are the most important part of the TCGAbiolinks package. Crafting a good query will allow you to find and download the desired data from the correct TCGA project. You may reference the user guide at any time for more information.

You can view a list of available projects by running the following command:

getGDCprojects()

The command for crafting queries is GDCquery(). Use ?GDCquery to view the command arguments. Not all arguments are required, but the more detailed your query, the more specific results you will receive.

After selecting a project, use getProjectSummary(project) to view available data categories.

TCGAbiolinks:::getProjectSummary("TCGA-COAD")
$data_categories

$case_count
[1] 461

$file_count
[1] 14320

$file_size
[1] 2.747049e+13

You can view available sample.types and data.types here.

Lets craft a query to download CNV data for project LUAD.

query <- GDCquery(project="TCGA-LUAD", data.category = "Copy Number Variation",
                  sample.type = "Primary solid Tumor", data.type = "Copy Number Segment")

Please note that capital letters and spelling of categories must match the database exactly. Sometimes the package lets you know that something is not correct, but not for all options. Heres an example with misspelled sample types and data types.

query <- GDCquery(project="TCGA-LUAD", data.category = "Copy Number Variation",
                  sample.type = "Primary Solid Tumor", data.type = "Copy Number Segment")

Downloading the data

After crafting a successful query, you can check the results to see what samples are included and the file names to be downloaded.

query <- GDCquery(project="TCGA-LUAD", data.category = "Copy Number Variation",
                  sample.type = "Primary solid Tumor", data.type = "Copy Number Segment")
--------------------------------------
o GDCquery: Searching in GDC database
--------------------------------------
Genome of reference: hg38
--------------------------------------------
oo Accessing GDC. This might take a while...
--------------------------------------------
ooo Project: TCGA-LUAD
--------------------
oo Filtering results
--------------------
ooo By data.type
ooo By sample.type
----------------
oo Checking data
----------------
ooo Check if there are duplicated cases
ooo Check if there results for the query
-------------------
o Preparing output
-------------------
query$results[[1]]
GDCdownload(query, files.per.chunk = 7) #sometimes if there are many files to be downloaded, it is best to break the download into chunks

Occassionally, the download will fail on the last file. Its an ongoing issue, but just re-run the command and the last will be downloaded.

Preparing the data

After downloading, the data needs to be in a form we can work with. GDCprepare collects each individual file, reads it in, then combines them.

luad.cnv.tumor <- GDCprepare(query)
head(luad.cnv.tumor)

Other data types

Lets download some rna-seq data

GDCdownload(query.norm)

Downloading data for project TCGA-CHOL
Of the 9 files for download 9 already exist.
All samples have been already downloaded
chol.tum <- GDCprepare(query.tum)

chol.tum <- GDCprepare(query.tum)
chol.norm <- GDCprepare(query.norm)

This type of data requires an extra step to put it in table format.

Clinical data

TCGA clinical data is also available for download. It can be downloaded by using the GDCquery_clinic() command:

coad.clin <- GDCquery_clinic("TCGA-COAD")
head(coad.clin)

Survival analysis can be performed using clinical data
